5. Honey bees are tricked into overworking by industry putting multiple queens to one hive making them think they have to produce more than they do.
6. Honey bees are extremely complex and social species, they have complicated brains which we still don't fully understand and yet these unnatural working environments cause colony collapse disorder. When a colony undergoes this, it is simply burned up and the next colony is put to work.

only the larvae eat the bee bread- adults can't actually eat solid food, since they just have proboscises (probosci?)- essentially just little straw-tongues for nectar. they don't actually need protein, since they stop growing and never molt as adults

only the oldest bees actually fly from the hive- exploring outside is dangerous, so newly hatched bees tend the larvae, then move on to building comb and cleaning, before finally being assigned the task of gathering outside for the rest of their lives. some bees also get designated as guards, and the mechanism for why a bee does or doesn't become a guard is unknown!


bees have one of the only working democracies in the animal kingdom. the queen doesn't actually rule, and the workers have full ability to control or even dethrone her. they also come to joint decisions when moving a hive, with initial bees exploring potential locations and dancing to tell their sisters, who also explore the location and repeat the dance if it's to their liking. with each individual forming their own educated opinion, they select the most ideal hive spot 97% of the time!


drones (or male bees) are actually haploid, while females are diploid. an unmated queen bee can only lay drone eggs, and only once she's mated can she lay female worker eggs


diet is actually the only difference between a queen bee and a worker. a worker is fed a special substance called royal jelly only for the first three days of her larval stage, while the queen is fed it exclusively through her whole life. this triggers the transformation of a worker into the much larger, and fertile, queen
